The following shows the outbound and inbound paths exercised via the standard daemon mode:

```bash
# Start a server with a tunnel defined in wg.conf
rustguard up wg0.conf

# Open enrollment for 60 seconds on a running server daemon
rustguard open 60

# Join from a client — enrollment flow executes, then tunnel loop starts
rustguard join 192.168.99.1:51820 --token mysecret

# Verify the tunnel is active and peers are established
rustguard status
```

After `join` completes, the tunnel loop is running. Packets flowing through the TUN interface follow the Outbound path described above; arriving UDP datagrams follow the Inbound path.

A minimal integration exercising the replay window boundary (counter 0 and counter 1):

```rust
// rustguard-core replay window — split check/update contract
let counter: u64 = incoming_packet.counter;

if !replay_window.check(counter) {
    // Duplicate or out-of-window — drop before decryption
    return Err(ReplayError::Duplicate);
}

// Decryption happens here (rustguard-crypto)
let plaintext = session.decrypt(&incoming_packet)?;

// Only advance the window after verified decryption
replay_window.update(counter);
```

---

### Checking replay protection before and after AEAD verification

```rust
use rustguard_core::{ReplayWindow, TransportSession};

fn receive_transport_packet(
    session: &mut TransportSession,
    window: &mut ReplayWindow,
    counter: u64,
    ciphertext: &[u8],
) -> Option<Vec<u8>> {
    // Step 1: reject duplicates before any crypto work
    if !window.check(counter) {
        return None;
    }

    // Step 2: AEAD decryption
    let plaintext = session.recv_key.decrypt(counter, ciphertext)?;

    // Step 3: only advance the window after the tag passes
    window.update(counter);

    Some(plaintext)
}
```

### Allocating an IP from the enrollment pool

```rust
use rustguard_enroll::{IpPool};
use std::net::Ipv4Addr;

let network = "10.150.0.0/24".parse().unwrap();
let mut pool = IpPool::new(network);

// Server takes .1 during initialization; clients call next()
let client_ip = pool.next().expect("pool exhausted");
println!("assigned: {}", client_ip); // 10.150.0.2
```

### Parsing a WireGuard wire message

```rust
use rustguard_core::WireMessage;

fn dispatch(raw: &[u8]) {
    match WireMessage::parse(raw) {
        Ok(WireMessage::HandshakeInitiation(msg)) => handle_initiation(msg),
        Ok(WireMessage::HandshakeResponse(msg))   => handle_response(msg),
        Ok(WireMessage::CookieReply(msg))         => handle_cookie(msg),
        Ok(WireMessage::Transport(pkt))           => handle_transport(pkt),
        Err(e) => eprintln!("parse error: {e}"),
    }
}
```

### Checking the enrollment window

```rust
use rustguard_enroll::EnrollmentWindow;

let mut window = EnrollmentWindow::default();

// Open by CLI: rustguard open 60
window.open(60);
assert!(window.is_open());

// New client attempts enrollment
if window.is_open() {
    // proceed with EnrollmentToken key exchange
}

// Close immediately: rustguard close
window.close();
assert!(!window.is_open());
```

